<tr>
<td bgcolor="#CECECE" class="btext" width="100%">Flashpoint 1985: Letters from the Cold War - <span class=bsmall>Wed 11 July 2001 01:36:45</span></td>
<td bgcolor="#CECECE" width=17><img src="images/item_icon.gif" width="17" height="17" alt="" border="0"></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td bgcolor="#EEEEEE" colspan=2>Malden, February 17th 1985<br><br>Dear Anna,<br><br>No doubt you have by now heard of the Russian attack on the NATO base on Everon, it must be all over the news. I write to tell you that I am alright, at least for now.<br><br>Last friday my platoon was decimated while trying to fall back to our strongholds to the south of Everon. I was the only survivor, but managed to slip into a forest and avoid the Russian patrols and helicopters to reach an evac point. To my horror, the camp was only inhabited by corpses - and reds. Before I even knew what happened, though, a bunch of militiamen who call themselves the Everon Resistance Front leaped out of nowhere and took out the Russian guards. They later helped me escape to the island of Malden by boat, where we have a larger garrison.<br><br>I hear things are about to get hot on this island too, so it is likely that you do not hear from me for a while. I do promise to write as often as I can though!<br><br>Love and kisses,<br><br>David<br><br>P.S. My new unit is low on experienced personnel, so I have been recommended for a line promotion and it is likely that I may get my own platoon in the next few days! Lieutenant Armstrong... doesn't it sound great?<br><br>-------------------------------<br><br>Malden, March 25th 1985<br><br>Happy birthday, dad!<br><br>How are things going back at home? Not as good as here, I bet. We're wiping the floor with those commies! Since I last wrote, I´ve moved on from the aging M60 (no offense dad, I know how much you loved that tank before you got that comfy desk job) to commanding my very own M1A1 Abrams. You wouldn't believe how good this beast is!<br><br>It can take almost any punishment - just yesterday a stray T80 managed to land a sabot round right on the side of our turret, and even that barely damaged the paint job! It did give us a bit of a headache, though. Luckily my commander (Colonel Forbes, you served together in the 32nd, right?) took care of the sucker before it could do any major harm.<br><br>Anyways dad, you'll be proud to know your son is following in your footsteps! This should be over in a matter of weeks.<br><br>Hugs,<br><br>Robert<br><br>-------------------------------<br><br>[CLASSIFIED -- BLACK OPS]<br><br>Everon, May 2nd 1985<br><br>Colonel Martin,<br><br>I have scouted the airfield near the N.E. coast as you ordered. The Russians have a single AA emplacement there, but it is well defended by ground units and relatively shielded from air attacks. There also seems to be medium to heavy helicopter presence, but I have not yet determined where their base of operations is. For now, here is a breakdown of the airstrip defenses:<br><br>-One Shilka AA Battery<br>-Two T72s (one of which is grounded for repairs, no clue as to whether it is operational)<br>-One T80<br>-Two BMP APCs<br>-Multiple infantry, 20, maybe 30, with at least one anti-armor platoon.<br>-Half a dozen supply trucks, including a single fuel tanker.<br><br>I reckon Cpt. Jackson and I can sneak in tomorrow night and set our last remaining satchel charges underneath the Shilka and possibly a couple of the tanks. If we time it right, we can cripple their defenses right in time for an airstrike. Can you commit a couple of Cobra choppers to this? All they'd need to do is take care of the remaining armor and thin out their troops; Jackson and I can mop up the rest while the cavalry arrives. Piece of cake, sir.<br><br>Godspeed,<br><br>Mjr. Gastowski<br><br>P.S. Can your courier bring us a replacement scope for Jackson's M21, and some more subsonic rounds for the MP5s?<br><br>-------------------------------<br><br>Everon, May 5th 1985<br><br>Beloved Anna,<br><br>We are back on Everon! This very morning, at dawn, we hit the northern beachhead of the island, near the airport. It was meant to have been a special forces job but the big boys were apparently needed elsewhere, so they sent us grunts instead.<br><br>The enemy positions had been pinpointed by scouts the previous night, so it was just a matter of peeling their defensive layers one by one until we reached their anti-aircraft platform. One of my men scored a direct hit on it with one of the LAWs, so I called in for some chopper support and the attack was over almost before it began, with very few casualties on our side.<br><br>Now the airport is ours, and we can use it as a base of operations to regain Everon, this could change the tide of the war! <br><br>Colonel Martin has personally commended me for the performance of my platoon, by the way. I may be in for another promotion, who knows?<br><br>I have a feeling I'll be home very soon... I can't wait to see you again.<br><br>Love and kisses,<br><br>David<br><br>-------------------------------<br><br>Kolgujev, July 7th 1985<br><br>Hey Pete,<br><br>I know I promised I'd be home for the fireworks... but this has dragged on a little longer than we expected. In any case, independence day wasn't exactly quiet: we flew an early morning sortie against a tank column, and two 'standard patrols'  which actually turned out to be pretty hot.<br><br>Best thing was, we caught a Hind stalking one of our convoys, from behind some treetops. He didn't notice us, and was hovering perfectly still, waiting for his prey to reach the hilltop, so we crept up to his six, about 30 feet off the ground. Tom,  my gunner, reckoned he had a good angle, but he said the chaingun might just bounce off the guy's armor, so the bastard went and fired a volley of AT rockets at him! Needless to say there were bits of Hind scattered all over Kolgujev.<br><br>I hear the chief is sending you to Top Gun. Is that true? I didn't think they liked your kind, but I bet you'll show them who's boss. By the way, they're having me practice with fixed-wing birds now. Apparently they're short of A10 pilots and need backup personnel, just in case. Hey, who knows, I may end up being a hotshot jock like you someday. Ha.<br><br>Take care Mav,<br><br>Sam</td>
</tr>
</table>
</td>
</tr>
